19/09/2006

 Greek Foreign Minister Dora Bakoyannis paid visits to Serbia and Kosovo starting on Thursday (14 September). In Belgrade, she met with President Boris Tadic and Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica. She told them that only a compromise would secure stability in the region. Bakoyannis brought a similar message to Pristina, where she met with Kosovo government and political party leaders, as well as with the head of the UN mission in the province, Joachim Ruecker. 
*** 
The UN Security Council held its third meeting this year on the Kosovo issue. Joachim Ruecker, warned the Council against postponing a decision on the province's status, saying resolution of the issue was vital to ensuring stability. Serbian envoy Sanda Raskovic-Ivic disagreed, saying "impatience and haste" would not lead to a sustainable solution. 
*** 
The US special co-ordinator for the fight against the Kurdistan Workers' Party, retired General Joseph Ralston, met in Ankara with his newly-appointed Turkish counterpart, retired General Edip Baser. Ralston voiced Washington's determination to combat any kind of terrorism, while warning against unilateral military action by Turkey in northern Iraq. 
*** 
A third round of negotiations on expanding the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) took place in Brussels starting on Wednesday (13 September). Representatives of current CEFTA members Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia and Romania held three days of talks with their counterparts from candidate countries Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Moldova, Montenegro and Serbia, as well as UNMIK. 
*** 
The new EU envoy to Albania, Germany's Helmuth Lohan, held talks with President Alfred Moisiu. The president assured him that Albania is determined to implement its Stabilisation and Association Agreement with the EU. 
*** 
 Albanian Prime Minister Sali Berisha paid a two-day visit to Athens that began on 12 September. He met with Greek President Karolos Papoulias, Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis, Parliament Speaker Anna Benaki-Psarouda, and other officials. An agreement on energy co-operation between Albania and Greece was signed during the visit. 
